Does Graph Prompt Work? A Data Operation Perspective with Theoretical Analysis

Qunzhong Wang, Xiangguo Sun‚àó, Hong Cheng.
Department of Systems Engineering and Engineering Management,
and Shun Hing Institute of Advanced Engineering
The Chinese University of Hong Kong
1155210998@link.cuhk.edu.hk, xiangguosun@cuhk.edu.hk
hcheng@se.cuhk.edu.hk Co-first AuthorsCorrespondence to: Xiangguo Sun (xiangguosun@cuhk.edu.hk)
Abstract

In recent years, graph prompting has emerged as a promising research direction, enabling the learning of additional tokens or subgraphs appended to the original graphs without requiring retraining of pre-trained graph models across various applications. This novel paradigm, shifting from the traditional ‚Äúpre-training and fine-tuning‚Äù to ‚Äúpre-training and prompting‚Äù has shown significant empirical success in simulating graph data operations, with applications ranging from recommendation systems to biological networks and graph transferring. However, despite its potential, the theoretical underpinnings of graph prompting remain underexplored, raising critical questions about its fundamental effectiveness. The lack of rigorous theoretical proof of why and how much it works is more like a ‚Äúdark cloud‚Äù over the graph prompt area to go further. To fill this gap, this paper introduces a theoretical framework that rigorously analyzes graph prompting from a data operation perspective. Our contributions are threefold: First, we provide a formal guarantee theorem, demonstrating graph prompts‚Äô capacity to approximate graph transformation operators, effectively linking upstream and downstream tasks. Second, we derive upper bounds on the error of these data operations by graph prompts for a single graph and extend this discussion to batches of graphs, which are common in graph model training. Third, we analyze the distribution of data operation errors, extending our theoretical findings from linear graph models (e.g., GCN) to non-linear graph models (e.g., GAT). Extensive experiments support our theoretical results and confirm the practical implications of these guarantees.

1 Introduction

Graph Neural Networks (GNNs) have been widely used in analyzing various graph-structured data. A standard workflow using GNNs is the ‚Äúpre-training and fine-tuning‚Äù paradigm, where a model is first trained on a large-scale, general-purpose dataset and then fine-tuned on a specific downstream task. While this method has been effective in transferring learned representations, it often needs many advanced tricks to retrain the model parameters for each new task, which can be computationally intensive and may not fully capture the unique characteristics of the downstream tasks, potentially limiting the model‚Äôs generalization.

Inspired by the success of prompting techniques in natural language processing (NLP), there has been a growing interest in adapting similar ideas to graph data through ‚Äúpre-training and prompting‚Äù. Graph prompts (Sun et¬†al., 2023b) modify the input graphs by adding learnable tokens or subgraphs, enabling the pre-trained GNN to better align with the requirements of downstream tasks without tuning the model parameters. Many empirical works (Sun et¬†al., 2022; Liu et¬†al., 2023; Tan et¬†al., 2023; Huang et¬†al., 2023; Ma et¬†al., 2023; Chen et¬†al., 2024) have found that graph prompting can reduce computational overhead, preserve the generality of the pre-trained model, and allow for seamless application across multiple tasks to achieve better expressive capability than the traditional paradigm.

Recently, some studies (Fang et¬†al., 2024; Sun et¬†al., 2023a) have realized that the reason why graph prompts work may relate to their capability in simulating various data operations like deleting/adding nodes/edges, changing node features, and even removing subgraphs. This makes graph prompts stand out from their counterpart in the NLP area and inspires many empirical applications like recommendation systems (Yang et¬†al., 2023; 2024; Wang et¬†al., 2024), biological networks (Diao et¬†al., 2022; Gao et¬†al., 2024), transferring knowledge across different graph domains (Guo et¬†al., 2023; Zhu et¬†al., 2024b; Zhao et¬†al., 2024), and more (Jin et¬†al., 2024). Unfortunately, despite these promising results, the theoretical basis of graph prompting remains underexplored. Existing works primarily rely on empirical validation and lack rigorous theoretical analysis to explain why graph prompts are effective and how they can be systematically designed. This gap is just like a ‚Äúdark could‚Äù over the graph prompt area, raising critical questions about their broader applications and the development of more advanced methods that could leverage their full potential.

In light of these limitations, this paper provides a comprehensive theoretical framework for graph prompting from a data operation perspective. First, we establish rigorous guarantee theorems that demonstrate the underlying reason why graph prompts work is their capacity to simulate various graph data operations, and our theorems further answer why such capacity can make the pre-trained model meet new task requirements without retraining. Second, we derive upper bounds on the error introduced by graph prompts when simulating these data operations. We analyze this error for individual graphs and extend our discussion to batches of graphs, which is crucial for understanding the scalability and generalization of graph prompts in practical scenarios where models are usually trained on multiple graphs. Third, we explore the distribution of the data operation error and extend our theoretical findings from linear graph models, such as Graph Convolutional Networks (GCNs), to non-linear models like Graph Attention Networks (GATs). This extension demonstrates the robustness of our theoretical framework across different GNN architectures and provides insights into how non-linearity affects the effectiveness of graph prompts. We conduct extensive experiments to confirm our theoretical findings. By offering such a solid theoretical foundation for graph prompting, our work advances the understanding of how and why graph prompts work, guides for designing more effective prompting techniques, and empowers researchers and practitioners to leverage them with greater confidence in various applications.

2 Background

Graph Prompt. Compared with ‚Äúpre-training and fine-tuning‚Äù, which first trains a graph model via some easily accessible task on the graph dataset and then tries to adapt the model to a new task (or even a new graph dataset), ‚Äúpre-training and prompting‚Äù aims to keep the pre-trained model unchanged but adjust the input data to make the downstream task compatible with the pre-training task. Without loss of generality, we assume all these tasks are graph level (e.g., graph classification). For node-level and edge-level tasks, many studies (Sun et¬†al., 2023a; Liu et¬†al., 2023) have proved that we can always find solutions to translate these tasks to the graph-level task.

GPF and All-in-One. Current graph prompt designs, as described in the review by Sun et¬†al. (2023b), can be primarily categorized into two types: prompt as token vectors added to node features, and prompt as additional graph inserted to the original graph. In the rest of this paper, we focus on two representative frameworks: GPF (Fang et¬†al., 2022) as an example of adding extra prompt vectors, and All-in-One (Sun et¬†al., 2023a) as an example of adding prompt subgraphs. Our choice is motivated by our interest in simulating graph operations at a theoretical level. The GPF and All-in-One frameworks provide the most fundamental approaches among these methods. The rest graph prompt designs can usually be treated as their special cases or natural extensions.

Motivations. Initially, Fang et¬†al. (2022) have proved that graph prompt can simulate any graph data operation (e.g., deleting/adding nodes/edges, changing node features, or removing subgraphs, etc). That means for any graph data operation t‚Å¢(‚ãÖ)ùë°‚ãÖt(\cdot)italic_t ( ‚ãÖ ), we can always learn a graph prompt reaching FŒ∏‚àó‚Å¢(Gœâ)=FŒ∏‚àó‚Å¢(t‚Å¢(G))subscriptùêπsuperscriptùúÉsubscriptùê∫ùúîsubscriptùêπsuperscriptùúÉùë°ùê∫F_{\theta^{*}}(G_{\omega})=F_{\theta^{*}}(t(G))italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) = italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_t ( italic_G ) ). However, this equivalence needs a very strong precondition: the graph model FùêπFitalic_F should not contain any non-linear layer, which is apparently very hard to meet in the practical solutions. Later, Sun et¬†al. (2023a) extended this finding with more advanced prompts and empirically observed that the error to such approximation FŒ∏‚àó‚Å¢(Gœâ)‚ÜíFŒ∏‚àó‚Å¢(t‚Å¢(G))‚ÜísubscriptùêπsuperscriptùúÉsubscriptùê∫ùúîsubscriptùêπsuperscriptùúÉùë°ùê∫F_{\theta^{*}}(G_{\omega})\rightarrow F_{\theta^{*}}(t(G))italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) ‚Üí italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_t ( italic_G ) ) may relate to the non-linear layers of the graph model and the prompt design. However, these observations are not followed by a critical theory proof. Recently, there has been an increasing number of empirical works on graph prompts achieving success in various applications. Unfortunately, the theoretical basis of graph prompt is still very tumbledown and we still have not figured out why graph prompts work in theory, especially for questions like how powerful the graph prompt is in manipulating graph data? and why such capability works for downstream tasks?

In this paper, we go deeper in theory for the graph prompt capability of manipulating data. We conduct a comprehensive effectiveness analysis of general graph prompt learning through the concepts of ‚Äúbridge sets‚Äù and ‚Äúœµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ-extended bridge sets‚Äù (see in section 3.3). Based on extensive theoretical derivations and substantial experimental evidence, we establish theorems related to the error bound of graph prompts in simulating graph data operations. Our goal is to figure out in theory how this error changes from a single graph to a batch of graphs, from a linear model to a non-linear model, and which factors relate to this error. Through this work, we wish to push forward the graph prompt area with a more solid theory basis, help researchers to design more scientific graph prompt techniques, and offer them theory confidence for their further usage.

3 Why Graph Prompt Works? A Data Operation Perspective

Let FŒ∏‚àósubscriptùêπsuperscriptùúÉF_{\theta^{*}}italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT be any given GNN model that has been pre-trained on a given task Tp‚Å¢r‚Å¢esubscriptùëáùëùùëüùëíT_{pre}italic_T start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p italic_r italic_e end_POSTSUBSCRIPT. Here Œ∏‚àósuperscriptùúÉ\theta^{*}italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT means the parameters have been determined and frozen. For a given graph instance Go‚Å¢r‚Å¢isubscriptùê∫ùëúùëüùëñG_{ori}italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_o italic_r italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, we can expect the model to output appropriate graph-level embedding on Tp‚Å¢r‚Å¢esubscriptùëáùëùùëüùëíT_{pre}italic_T start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p italic_r italic_e end_POSTSUBSCRIPT because this model has already been trained on this task. However, when we try to use this model on a new task Td‚Å¢o‚Å¢wsubscriptùëáùëëùëúùë§T_{dow}italic_T start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_d italic_o italic_w end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, the output embedding, FŒ∏‚àó‚Å¢(Go‚Å¢r‚Å¢i)subscriptùêπsuperscriptùúÉsubscriptùê∫ùëúùëüùëñF_{\theta^{*}}(G_{ori})italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_o italic_r italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ), can not guarantee acceptable performance because the pre-training task Tp‚Å¢r‚Å¢esubscriptùëáùëùùëüùëíT_{pre}italic_T start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p italic_r italic_e end_POSTSUBSCRIPT may be incompatible with downstream tasks Td‚Å¢o‚Å¢wsubscriptùëáùëëùëúùë§T_{dow}italic_T start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_d italic_o italic_w end_POSTSUBSCRIPT.

3.1 Perspective from Model Tuning

To fill this gap, ‚Äúpre-training and fine-tuning‚Äù aims to adapt the pre-trained model to a new version and wish it could perform better. Assume there exists an optimal function, say Cùê∂Citalic_C, which can map Go‚Å¢r‚Å¢isubscriptùê∫ùëúùëüùëñG_{ori}italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_o italic_r italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT to the embedding C‚Å¢(Go‚Å¢r‚Å¢i)ùê∂subscriptùê∫ùëúùëüùëñC(G_{ori})italic_C ( italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_o italic_r italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) to achieve good performance on Td‚Å¢o‚Å¢wsubscriptùëáùëëùëúùë§T_{dow}italic_T start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_d italic_o italic_w end_POSTSUBSCRIPT. The nature of ‚Äúpre-training and fine-tuning‚Äù is to hope the fine-tuned graph model could approximate to C‚Å¢(Go‚Å¢r‚Å¢i)ùê∂subscriptùê∫ùëúùëüùëñC(G_{ori})italic_C ( italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_o italic_r italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ):

FŒ∏‚àó‚ÜíŒ∏#‚Å¢(Go‚Å¢r‚Å¢i)‚ÜíC‚Å¢(Go‚Å¢r‚Å¢i)‚Üísubscriptùêπ‚ÜísuperscriptùúÉsuperscriptùúÉ#subscriptùê∫ùëúùëüùëñùê∂subscriptùê∫ùëúùëüùëñF_{\theta^{*}\rightarrow\theta^{\#}}(G_{ori})\rightarrow C(G_{ori})italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Üí italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT # end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_o italic_r italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) ‚Üí italic_C ( italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_o italic_r italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) (2)

However, achieving this goal usually requires fine-tuning the graph model, which is not always efficient and needs many empirical tuning tricks. The tuning course may be even harder if the pre-trained model is ill-designed for the downstream task. In addition, we can not guarantee that fine-tuning the pre-trained model (i.e. Œ∏‚àó‚ÜíŒ∏#‚ÜísuperscriptùúÉsuperscriptùúÉ#\theta^{*}\rightarrow\theta^{\#}italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Üí italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT # end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT) can always surpass training the model from scratch because the preserved knowledge may contribute negatively to the downstream task.

3.2 Perspective from Data Operation

Instead of the above model-level tricks, graph prompts provide a data-level alternative. Some prior works (Fang et¬†al., 2024; Sun et¬†al., 2023a) have initially proved that graph prompts can simulate any graph operations (e.g., deleting/adding nodes/edges/subgraphs, changing node features, etc). However, how effective of graph prompt is and why this works for the new task are still not yet answered. To answer these questions, we first explain our data operation perspective by a theorem as follows:

Theorem 1.

Let FŒ∏‚àósubscriptùêπsuperscriptùúÉF_{\theta^{*}}italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT be a GNN model pre-trained on task Tp‚Å¢r‚Å¢esubscriptùëáùëùùëüùëíT_{pre}italic_T start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p italic_r italic_e end_POSTSUBSCRIPT with frozen parameters (Œ∏‚àósuperscriptùúÉ\theta^{*}italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT); let Td‚Å¢o‚Å¢wsubscriptùëáùëëùëúùë§T_{dow}italic_T start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_d italic_o italic_w end_POSTSUBSCRIPT be the downstream task and Cùê∂Citalic_C is an optimal function to Td‚Å¢o‚Å¢wsubscriptùëáùëëùëúùë§T_{dow}italic_T start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_d italic_o italic_w end_POSTSUBSCRIPT. Given any graph Go‚Å¢r‚Å¢isubscriptùê∫ùëúùëüùëñG_{ori}italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_o italic_r italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, C‚Å¢(Gori)ùê∂subscriptùê∫oriC(G_{\text{ori}})italic_C ( italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT ori end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) denotes the optimal embedding vector to the downstream task (i.e. can be parsed to yield correct results for Gorisubscriptùê∫oriG_{\text{ori}}italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT ori end_POSTSUBSCRIPT in the downstream task), then there always exists a bridge graph Gb‚Å¢r‚Å¢isubscriptùê∫ùëèùëüùëñG_{bri}italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b italic_r italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT such that FŒ∏‚àó‚Å¢(Gb‚Å¢r‚Å¢i)=C‚Å¢(Go‚Å¢r‚Å¢i)subscriptùêπsuperscriptùúÉsubscriptùê∫ùëèùëüùëñùê∂subscriptùê∫ùëúùëüùëñF_{\theta^{*}}(G_{bri})=C(G_{ori})italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b italic_r italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) = italic_C ( italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_o italic_r italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ).

A detailed proof of Theorem 1 can be seen in Appendix A.3.1, from which we can find that for any given graph Go‚Å¢r‚Å¢isubscriptùê∫ùëúùëüùëñG_{ori}italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_o italic_r italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, there always exists a bridge graph, say Gb‚Å¢r‚Å¢isubscriptùê∫ùëèùëüùëñG_{bri}italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b italic_r italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, making the following equation hold:

FŒ∏‚àó‚Å¢(Gb‚Å¢r‚Å¢i)=C‚Å¢(Go‚Å¢r‚Å¢i)subscriptùêπsuperscriptùúÉsubscriptùê∫ùëèùëüùëñùê∂subscriptùê∫ùëúùëüùëñF_{\theta^{*}}(G_{bri})=C(G_{ori})italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b italic_r italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) = italic_C ( italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_o italic_r italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) (3)

That means, without needing to tune the model, we can try to find a data operation method that translates Go‚Å¢r‚Å¢isubscriptùê∫ùëúùëüùëñG_{ori}italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_o italic_r italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT to Gb‚Å¢r‚Å¢isubscriptùê∫ùëèùëüùëñG_{bri}italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b italic_r italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT with the pre-trained model unchanged. Graph prompts can be treated as a learnable data operation framework to help us manipulate these graph data. In this way, we can significantly reduce the difficulty of traditional fine-tuning work, improve the performance on a new task (or even a new dataset), and further enhance the generalization of graph neural networks. With this perspective, our next question is: How difficult to find such a bridge graph using graph prompts?

3.3 Measuring the Difficulty of Finding Bridge Graphs via Graph Prompts

Graph prompts can be viewed as a type of graph transformation operator. For example, the simplest graph prompt is just adding a specific prompt token vector pœâsubscriptùëùùúîp_{\omega}italic_p start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT to each node feature of the graph and then we can transform this graph Gùê∫Gitalic_G into a family of graphs {Pœâ‚Å¢(G)|œâ‚àà‚ÑùF}conditional-setsubscriptùëÉùúîùê∫ùúîsuperscript‚Ñùùêπ\{P_{\omega}(G)|\omega\in\mathbb{R}^{F}\}{ italic_P start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G ) | italic_œâ ‚àà blackboard_R start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_F end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT }, where Pœâ‚Å¢(G)subscriptùëÉùúîùê∫P_{\omega}(G)italic_P start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G ) represents the output graph obtained by graph prompt on Gùê∫Gitalic_G. Once œâùúî\omegaitalic_œâ is determined, the corresponding data transformation rule and unique output graph data are also defined. This family can be understood as the ‚Äútransformation space‚Äù of graph Gùê∫Gitalic_G under prompt PùëÉPitalic_P, denoted as DP‚Å¢(G)subscriptùê∑ùëÉùê∫D_{P}(G)italic_D start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_P end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G ). In this process, we achieve seamless alignment of upstream and downstream tasks solely through data transformation operators, without relying on tuning the model‚Äôs parameters.

Definition 1 (Bridge Set and œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ-extended Bridge Set).

The bridge set of a graph Gùê∫Gitalic_G is defined as:

BG={Gp‚à£FŒ∏‚àó‚Å¢(Gp)=C‚Å¢(G)}subscriptùêµùê∫conditional-setsubscriptùê∫ùëùsubscriptùêπsuperscriptùúÉsubscriptùê∫ùëùùê∂ùê∫B_{G}=\{G_{p}\mid F_{\theta^{*}}(G_{p})=C(G)\}italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = { italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ‚à£ italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) = italic_C ( italic_G ) }

where FŒ∏‚àósubscriptùêπsuperscriptùúÉF_{\theta^{*}}italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT is the frozen graph model from the pre-training task, and Cùê∂Citalic_C is the optimal function for the downstream task. The œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ-extended bridge set of Gùê∫Gitalic_G is a relaxed version of the bridge set, which is defined as:

œµ‚Å¢-‚Å¢BG={Gp‚à£œµ=‚ÄñFŒ∏‚àó‚Å¢(Gp)‚àíC‚Å¢(G)‚Äñ‚â§œµ‚àó}.italic-œµ-subscriptùêµùê∫conditional-setsubscriptùê∫ùëùitalic-œµnormsubscriptùêπsuperscriptùúÉsubscriptùê∫ùëùùê∂ùê∫superscriptitalic-œµ\epsilon\text{-}B_{G}=\{G_{p}\mid\epsilon=\|F_{\theta^{*}}(G_{p})-C(G)\|\leq% \epsilon^{*}\}.italic_œµ - italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = { italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ‚à£ italic_œµ = ‚à• italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) - italic_C ( italic_G ) ‚à• ‚â§ italic_œµ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT } .

Achieving a transformation exactly equivalent to C‚Å¢(G)ùê∂ùê∫C(G)italic_C ( italic_G ) is highly non-parametric and nonlinear. Finding the corresponding Gbrisubscriptùê∫briG_{\text{bri}}italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT bri end_POSTSUBSCRIPT or even the bridge set for any Gorisubscriptùê∫oriG_{\text{ori}}italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT ori end_POSTSUBSCRIPT involves solving complex, high-order nonlinear equations. This task becomes virtually impossible manually, especially if the pre-training method integrates multiple tasks or intricate mechanisms. Fortunately, graph prompts PœâsubscriptùëÉùúîP_{\omega}italic_P start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT can be viewed as parameterized fitting for these operators and they usually contain very lightweight parameters, which dramatically simplify the search space compared with manually designed strategies. The effectiveness of graph prompting methods hinges on their ability to approximate these operators closely‚Äîwhether they can uniformly project Gùê∫Gitalic_G in the dataset into the bridge set BGsubscriptùêµùê∫B_{G}italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, or at least map them into the extended bridge set with a small upper error bound œµ‚àósuperscriptitalic-œµ\epsilon^{*}italic_œµ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT.

4 The Upper Bound of Data Operation Error via Graph Prompt

4.1 Upper Bound of the Error on A Single Graph

Here we aim to demonstrate that using graph prompts provided by frameworks such as GPF and All-in-One, denoted as parameterized operators PœâsubscriptùëÉùúîP_{\omega}italic_P start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT with parameter œâùúî\omegaitalic_œâ, can consistently project Gùê∫Gitalic_G into an œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ-extended BGsubscriptùêµùê∫B_{G}italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, where œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ has a uniform upper bound. This would initially validate the effectiveness of graph prompting methods in leveraging the potential of pre-trained models without compromising their expressive power. If Gùê∫Gitalic_G can be seamlessly projected into BGsubscriptùêµùê∫B_{G}italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT or an œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ-extended BGsubscriptùêµùê∫B_{G}italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT (for small œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ), it would indicate excellent performance and full utilization of the model‚Äôs capabilities.

To this end, we first conduct a quantitative analysis of PœâsubscriptùëÉùúîP_{\omega}italic_P start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT‚Äôs graph transformation approximation ability on a single graph. With our proposed data operation perspective, we can reformulate the findings in Fang et¬†al. (2022) as follows:

Theorem 2.

Given a GPF-like prompt vector pœâsubscriptùëùùúîp_{\omega}italic_p start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, if a GCN model FŒ∏subscriptùêπùúÉF_{\theta}italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT does not have any non-linear transformations, then there exists an optimal œâùúî\omegaitalic_œâ for any input graph Gùê∫Gitalic_G such that Pœâ‚Å¢(G)‚ààBGsubscriptùëÉùúîùê∫subscriptùêµùê∫P_{\omega}(G)\in B_{G}italic_P start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G ) ‚àà italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT.

This theorem is proved by Fang et¬†al. (2022) but it‚Äôs important to note that all GNN models employ non-linear transformations. According to the function approximation theorem for neural networks (Hornik et¬†al., 1989), the core of improving a model‚Äôs approximation and simulation ability lies in its non-linear components. Removing these non-linear parts would limit the model to approximating only linear transformations and functions. To demonstrate the effectiveness of graph prompt learning in real downstream tasks, we offer the following theorems further:

Theorem 3.

Given a GPF-like prompt vector pœâsubscriptùëùùúîp_{\omega}italic_p start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, if a GCN model FŒ∏subscriptùêπùúÉF_{\theta}italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT has non-linear function layers but the model‚Äôs weight matrix is row full-rank, then there exists an optimal œâùúî\omegaitalic_œâ for any input graph Gùê∫Gitalic_G such that Pœâ‚Å¢(G)‚ààBGsubscriptùëÉùúîùê∫subscriptùêµùê∫P_{\omega}(G)\in B_{G}italic_P start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G ) ‚àà italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT.

Theorem 4.

Given the All-in-One-like prompt graph S‚Å¢GœâùëÜsubscriptùê∫ùúîSG_{\omega}italic_S italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, if a GCN model FŒ∏subscriptùêπùúÉF_{\theta}italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT does not have any non-linear transformations, or has non-linear layers but the model‚Äôs weight matrix is row full-rank, then there exists an optimal œâùúî\omegaitalic_œâ for any input graph Gùê∫Gitalic_G such that Pœâ‚Å¢(G)‚ààBGsubscriptùëÉùúîùê∫subscriptùêµùê∫P_{\omega}(G)\in B_{G}italic_P start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G ) ‚àà italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT.

Theorems 3 and 4 are proved in Appendix A.3.2. Although we‚Äôve only added the row full-rank condition, these two theorems significantly expand the applicability of Theorem 2. According to Pennington & Worah (2017), well-trained models mostly contain full-rank matrices, which can be easily guaranteed by some tricks like orthogonal initialization, He initialization, etc. Raghu et¬†al. (2017) also find that a full-rank parameter matrix in the model usually indicates stronger expressiveness. Intuitively, a weight matrix in the graph model usually indicates how to project the input graph into some latent embedding for the downstream task. According to the basic knowledge of linear algebra, when the weight matrix is row full-rank, we can always restore the input from the output. That means we can always find an appropriate input format to meet various downstream requirements. Therefore, from a practical empirical perspective, we can assume that in most cases, both GPF-like and All-in-One-like frameworks can achieve seamless projection of Gùê∫Gitalic_G into BGsubscriptùêµùê∫B_{G}italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, demonstrating the effectiveness and rationality of graph prompting.

For the cases where weight matrices are not full-rank, we have found that the error value (œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ) of the extended bridge set (œµ‚àíBGitalic-œµsubscriptùêµùê∫\epsilon-B_{G}italic_œµ - italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT), into which the prompting framework can map Gùê∫Gitalic_G, is positively correlated with the distance of the graph model parameter matrix from being full-rank. However, a consistent upper bound does exist for the error œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ of the extended bridge set when the matrix rank is determined. This means that even in some extreme cases, graph prompt learning can still guarantee a certain level of performance without experiencing extremely unexpectedly poor results:

Theorem 5.

For a GCN model FŒ∏subscriptùêπùúÉF_{\theta}italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, assume at least one layer‚Äôs parameter matrix is not full rank, for GPF or All-in-One prompt, there exists an upper bound of œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ such that for any input graph Gùê∫Gitalic_G, there exists an optimal œâùúî\omegaitalic_œâ where Pœâ‚Å¢(G)‚ààœµ‚Å¢-‚Å¢BGsubscriptùëÉùúîùê∫italic-œµ-subscriptùêµùê∫P_{\omega}(G)\in\epsilon\text{-}B_{G}italic_P start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G ) ‚àà italic_œµ - italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, with œµ‚â§Œº‚Å¢(Œ∏‚àó)‚ãÖŒª‚Å¢(G)italic-œµ‚ãÖùúásuperscriptùúÉùúÜùê∫\epsilon\leq\mu(\theta^{*})\cdot\lambda(G)italic_œµ ‚â§ italic_Œº ( italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ) ‚ãÖ italic_Œª ( italic_G ), where Œº‚Å¢(Œ∏‚àó)ùúásuperscriptùúÉ\mu(\theta^{*})italic_Œº ( italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ) and Œª‚Å¢(G)ùúÜùê∫\lambda(G)italic_Œª ( italic_G ) correspond to the model and graph Gùê∫Gitalic_G, respectively.

Theorem 5 is proved in Appendix A.3.3, where the upper bound of the error œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ can be further expressed as follows:

Œº‚Å¢(Œ∏‚àó)‚Å¢Œª‚Å¢(G)=sin‚Å°(Œ¶/2)‚Å¢‚ÄñC‚Å¢(G)‚ÄñùúásuperscriptùúÉùúÜùê∫Œ¶2normùê∂ùê∫\mu(\theta^{*})\lambda(G)=\sin(\Phi/2)\|C(G)\|italic_Œº ( italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ) italic_Œª ( italic_G ) = roman_sin ( roman_Œ¶ / 2 ) ‚à• italic_C ( italic_G ) ‚à• (4)

The upper bound has two terms, one part is related to the model because sin‚Å°(Œ¶/2)Œ¶2\sin(\Phi/2)roman_sin ( roman_Œ¶ / 2 ) can be treated as a measurement of the model‚Äôs expressiveness, the details of which can be seen in Appendix A.3.3. The other part is related to ‚ÄñC‚Å¢(G)‚Äñnormùê∂ùê∫\|C(G)\|‚à• italic_C ( italic_G ) ‚à•. Since the graph prompt aims to approximate Gùê∫Gitalic_G with Pœâ‚Å¢(Go‚Å¢r‚Å¢i)subscriptùëÉùúîsubscriptùê∫ùëúùëüùëñP_{\omega}(G_{ori})italic_P start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_o italic_r italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ), that means the error is also related to the prompt design. In this way, we in theory confirm the intuitional findings by Sun et¬†al. (2023a) as mentioned in our motivation section.

The upper bound of œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ given in Theorem 5 reveals the potential distortion of BGsubscriptùêµùê∫B_{G}italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT‚Äôs shape when the matrix is not full-rank and the model‚Äôs expressive power is insufficient. This can lead to an increased distance between BGsubscriptùêµùê∫B_{G}italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and the transformation domain DP‚Å¢(G)subscriptùê∑ùëÉùê∫D_{P}(G)italic_D start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_P end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G ) (see this term in section 3.3) of GPF or All-in-One prompts. To confirm this judgment, we conducted a quantitative analysis using numerical methods for the case of non-full rank matrices. We make the graph model weight matrix be not full-rank (with rank n‚àírùëõùëün-ritalic_n - italic_r where nùëõnitalic_n is the full rank number and r=0,‚ãØ‚Å¢nùëü0‚ãØùëõr=0,\cdots nitalic_r = 0 , ‚ãØ italic_n) and use the distance between the embedding vectors of Pœâ‚Å¢(G)subscriptùëÉùúîùê∫P_{\omega}(G)italic_P start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G ) and C‚Å¢(G)ùê∂ùê∫C(G)italic_C ( italic_G ) as the loss function. We applied stochastic gradient descent with a learning rate of 0.0001 to optimize œâùúî\omegaitalic_œâ until convergence. To avoid local optima, we repeated the process multiple times with different initializations for each graph. The results are shown in Figure 1, where the vertical axis is the empirical max œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ of the extended BGsubscriptùêµùê∫B_{G}italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and the horizontal axis is rùëüritalic_r where r=0,1,2,‚ãØ,9,10ùëü012‚ãØ910r=0,1,2,\cdots,9,10italic_r = 0 , 1 , 2 , ‚ãØ , 9 , 10, making the matrix rank become n‚àírùëõùëün-ritalic_n - italic_r. From Figure 1 we can find that with the increase of rùëüritalic_r, the rank of the model matrix becomes lower, making the model expressiveness worse and then leading to a larger error bound. Besides, more advanced graph prompts (e.g., GPF-Plus, All-in-One, and All-in-One-Plus) generally have a lower bound than the naive one (e.g., GPF).

4.2 Extend the Error Bound Discussion to A Batch of Graphs

In Sections 3 and 4.1, we have proved that graph prompting frameworks can indeed fit graph transformation operators given a single graph, thereby exploiting model capabilities. However, in other cases, we often train the model via a batch of graphs and seek to find better performance over the whole graph dataset. Correspondingly, we should aspire to transform each graph Gùê∫Gitalic_G in the downstream dataset into its corresponding BGsubscriptùêµùê∫B_{G}italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT or œµ‚Å¢-‚Å¢BGitalic-œµ-subscriptùêµùê∫\epsilon\text{-}B_{G}italic_œµ - italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT (for small œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ). If such a uniform upper bound œµ‚àósuperscriptitalic-œµ\epsilon^{*}italic_œµ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT exists, it would theoretically validate the excellent performance of graph prompting in general downstream tasks, confirming the rational utilization of powerful upstream models.

For a batch of graphs, the complexity and information contained in the graph prompt become particularly important. For instance, the increased number of prompt vectors in GPF (a.k.a GPF-Plus) and the selection of a larger size of the prompt graph in All-in-One greatly expand the transformation space of graph Gùê∫Gitalic_G under prompt PùëÉPitalic_P (see DP‚Å¢(‚ãÖ)subscriptùê∑ùëÉ‚ãÖD_{P}(\cdot)italic_D start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_P end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( ‚ãÖ ) in section 3.3). A larger transformation space corresponds to a smaller œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ upper bound. In our theoretical analysis, we found that when the prompt takes an overly simple form, the capability of prompt learning is limited. This manifests as a theoretical lower bound of the bridge set extension as suggested in Theorem 6:

Theorem 6.

For a GCN model FŒ∏subscriptùêπùúÉF_{\theta}italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, for GPF with a single prompt vector or All-in-One with a single-token graph prompt, given a batch of graphs ùí¢={G1,‚ãØ,Gi,‚ãØ,Gn}ùí¢subscriptùê∫1‚ãØsubscriptùê∫ùëñ‚ãØsubscriptùê∫ùëõ\mathcal{G}=\{G_{1},\cdots,G_{i},\cdots,G_{n}\}caligraphic_G = { italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , ‚ãØ , italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , ‚ãØ , italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUBSCRIPT }, the root mean squared error (RMSE) over {œµ1,‚ãØ,œµn}subscriptitalic-œµ1‚ãØsubscriptitalic-œµùëõ\{\epsilon_{1},\cdots,\epsilon_{n}\}{ italic_œµ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , ‚ãØ , italic_œµ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUBSCRIPT } has a lower bound œµosuperscriptitalic-œµùëú\epsilon^{o}italic_œµ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_o end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT such that R‚Å¢M‚Å¢S‚Å¢E‚Å¢(œµ1,‚ãØ,œµn)‚â•œµoùëÖùëÄùëÜùê∏subscriptitalic-œµ1‚ãØsubscriptitalic-œµùëõsuperscriptitalic-œµùëúRMSE(\epsilon_{1},\cdots,\epsilon_{n})\geq\epsilon^{o}italic_R italic_M italic_S italic_E ( italic_œµ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , ‚ãØ , italic_œµ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) ‚â• italic_œµ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_o end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT.

Theorem 6 is proved in Appendix A.3.4 and we also give the detailed formulation of œµosuperscriptitalic-œµùëú\epsilon^{o}italic_œµ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_o end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT in the proof, from which we can find that œµosuperscriptitalic-œµùëú\epsilon^{o}italic_œµ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_o end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT is related to graph data and the prompt token. This indicates that when the downstream task dataset is relatively large, we must correspondingly increase the transformation space of the prompt to better utilize the model‚Äôs capabilities, which also aligns with existing empirical observations (Liu et¬†al., 2021). Then our next question is: With the increase of graphs, how does graph prompt complexity increase with their error bound increased?

Intuitively, a good graph prompt should not increase its complexity faster than the growth of the dataset because in that case the effectiveness of prompt learning in practical applications would be significantly compromised. Fortunately, we found that for relatively large datasets, the scale of prompts required for prompt learning is highly controllable with the number of needed tokens for the prompt almost constant, far from the increase of graphs. This explains why even with relatively large downstream datasets, as reflected in Sun et¬†al. (2023a), empirical results using medium-scale prompts can still achieve excellent outcomes. Compared to fine-tuning the entire model parameters, Theorem 7 (see the proof in Appendix A.3.4) indicates why graph prompting can achieve comparable or even better results with less parameter adjustment scale:

The eigenvalues of VùëâVitalic_V sorted by the descending order can be denoted as {Œª1,‚ãØ,ŒªM}subscriptùúÜ1‚ãØsubscriptùúÜùëÄ\{\lambda_{1},\cdots,\lambda_{M}\}{ italic_Œª start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , ‚ãØ , italic_Œª start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_M end_POSTSUBSCRIPT }. In practice, the eigenvalues of VùëâVitalic_V in datasets often exhibit an exponential decay (Johnstone, 2001). This explains the rapid decrease in error rate as kùëòkitalic_k increases, proving that prompts are not only effective but also efficient. With the increasing number of graphs MùëÄMitalic_M in the dataset, the largest kùëòkitalic_k (k‚â™Mmuch-less-thanùëòùëÄk\ll Mitalic_k ‚â™ italic_M) eigenvalues can almost explain most of the matrix, which means using small-scaled prompt tokens can achieve reasonably accurate results. This finding is also consistent with many existing empirical researches (Liu et¬†al., 2023; Sun et¬†al., 2023a; Wang et¬†al., 2024; Zhu et¬†al., 2024a; Zi et¬†al., 2024).

4.3 Value Distribution of the Data Operation Error with Graph Prompt

In the previous sections, we established a theoretical upper bound of œµ‚â§œµ‚àóitalic-œµsuperscriptitalic-œµ\epsilon\leq\epsilon^{*}italic_œµ ‚â§ italic_œµ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, allowing the graph prompt PœâsubscriptùëÉùúîP_{\omega}italic_P start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT to map a given graph Gùê∫Gitalic_G into the œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ-extended BGsubscriptùêµùê∫B_{G}italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT range. However, the conditions to reach this upper bound are often difficult to meet, making the theoretical upper bound usually correspond to some corner cases which may be not that practical in processing empirical experimental analysis. To offer stronger practical guidance for researchers‚Äô general experimental purposes, the value distribution of œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ (a.k.a ‚Äúerror range‚Äù), comes to our next point of interest. The error range analysis indicates a quantitative degree of the bridge set extension, which includes estimating the mean, and variance, and finding the approximate distribution pattern.

Definition 2 (Graph Embedding Residual Vector).

Consider a graph model with Leaky-Relu as their activation function, we denote the graph embedding residual vector as ùõÉ‚àà‚Ñù1√óFùõÉsuperscript‚Ñù1ùêπ\bm{\beta}\in\mathbb{R}^{1\times F}bold_italic_Œ≤ ‚àà blackboard_R start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 1 √ó italic_F end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT where FùêπFitalic_F is the graph embedding dimensions. Then we theoretically find that œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ conforms to the Chi distribution (œáksubscriptùúíùëò\chi_{k}italic_œá start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_k end_POSTSUBSCRIPT):

Theorem 8.

Given a GCN model FŒ∏subscriptùêπùúÉF_{\theta}italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT with the last layer parameter matrix having rank F‚àírùêπùëüF-ritalic_F - italic_r (FùêπFitalic_F is the graph embedding dimension, rùëüritalic_r is the rank lost), an input graph Gùê∫Gitalic_G, for the optimal œâùúî\omegaitalic_œâ, Pœâ‚Å¢(G)‚ààœµ‚Å¢-‚Å¢BGsubscriptùëÉùúîùê∫italic-œµ-subscriptùêµùê∫P_{\omega}(G)\in\epsilon\text{-}B_{G}italic_P start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G ) ‚àà italic_œµ - italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT. If the Graph Embedding Residuals follow the i.i.d. normal distribution, then œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ follows a Chi distribution œársubscriptùúíùëü\chi_{r}italic_œá start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_r end_POSTSUBSCRIPT with rùëüritalic_r free variables.

We give the proof of Theorem 8 in Appendix A.3.5. In the practical settings, the distribution of graph residual terms may slightly diverge from i.i.d. normal distribution, making the real distribution of œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ a little different from standard œáksubscriptùúíùëò\chi_{k}italic_œá start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_k end_POSTSUBSCRIPT. Besides, there is also a theoretical upper bound œµ‚àósuperscriptitalic-œµ\epsilon^{*}italic_œµ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, making the real distribution of œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ more like a truncated œáksubscriptùúíùëò\chi_{k}italic_œá start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_k end_POSTSUBSCRIPT. The statistical measures of this distribution can be easily obtained as follows:

Corollary 1 (Statistical Measures and Confidence Values of œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ).

The mean of œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ is c‚Å¢2‚Å¢Œì‚Å¢((r+1)/2)Œì‚Å¢(r/2)ùëê2Œìùëü12Œìùëü2c\sqrt{2}\frac{\Gamma((r+1)/2)}{\Gamma(r/2)}italic_c square-root start_ARG 2 end_ARG divide start_ARG roman_Œì ( ( italic_r + 1 ) / 2 ) end_ARG start_ARG roman_Œì ( italic_r / 2 ) end_ARG, the variance is c2‚Å¢(r‚àí2‚Å¢[Œì‚Å¢((r+1)/2)]2[Œì‚Å¢(r/2)]2)superscriptùëê2ùëü2superscriptdelimited-[]Œìùëü122superscriptdelimited-[]Œìùëü22c^{2}\left(r-2\frac{[\Gamma((r+1)/2)]^{2}}{[\Gamma(r/2)]^{2}}\right)italic_c start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ( italic_r - 2 divide start_ARG [ roman_Œì ( ( italic_r + 1 ) / 2 ) ] start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_ARG start_ARG [ roman_Œì ( italic_r / 2 ) ] start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_ARG ), and confidence values can be obtained through Cœár,psuperscriptsubscriptùê∂ùúíùëüùëùC_{\chi}^{r,p}italic_C start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œá end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_r , italic_p end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT using numerical methods or table lookup, where c is the scaling factor compared to the standard distribution, and r is the number of dimensions lost compared to a full-rank matrix.

To further confirm our theoretical findings, we compare the real-world distribution of œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ with 4 commonly used distribution patterns (Chi, Chi-square, Exponential, and Gamma). Figure 2 presents the fitting results and Table 1 shows the pùëùpitalic_p-value significance, from which we can see that the Chi distribution provides the best approximation within a non-extreme range of œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ.

4.4 Extend the Discussion from Linear Models to Non-linear Models

While our previous analysis focused on GCN or linear aggregation models that can be represented in the form of ‚Äúdiffusion matrices‚Äù, many advanced models utilizing attention mechanisms exhibit distinctly different characteristics. Their aggregation methods involve the computation of attention matrices, which in turn depend on the node feature vectors of Gùê∫Gitalic_G. This can be considered as a non-linear model w.r.t Gùê∫Gitalic_G‚Äôs feature matrix. In our analysis, we use Graph Attention Networks (GAT) as an exemplar, as the attention mechanism in GAT is a common component in many non-linear models. Fortunately, the guarantees provided by our theorems do not differ significantly for these models. This indicates that even as models become more non-linear and complex, graph prompting can still effectively harness the powerful capabilities of pre-trained models:

Theorem 9.

Let FŒ∏subscriptùêπùúÉF_{\theta}italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT be a GAT model. If any layer of the model has a full row rank parameter matrix, then for the All-in-One prompting framework, for any input graph G, there exists an optimal œâùúî\omegaitalic_œâ such that Pœâ‚Å¢(G)‚ààBGsubscriptùëÉùúîùê∫subscriptùêµùê∫P_{\omega}(G)\in B_{G}italic_P start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G ) ‚àà italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT. When the parameter matrix is not full rank, there is an upper bound Œº‚Å¢(Œ∏)‚ãÖŒª‚Å¢(G)‚ãÖùúáùúÉùúÜùê∫\mu(\theta)\cdot\lambda(G)italic_Œº ( italic_Œ∏ ) ‚ãÖ italic_Œª ( italic_G ) making Pœâ‚Å¢(G)‚ààœµ‚Å¢-‚Å¢BGsubscriptùëÉùúîùê∫italic-œµ-subscriptùêµùê∫P_{\omega}(G)\in\epsilon\text{-}B_{G}italic_P start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G ) ‚àà italic_œµ - italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, œµ‚â§Œº‚Å¢(Œ∏)‚ãÖŒª‚Å¢(G)italic-œµ‚ãÖùúáùúÉùúÜùê∫\epsilon\leq\mu(\theta)\cdot\lambda(G)italic_œµ ‚â§ italic_Œº ( italic_Œ∏ ) ‚ãÖ italic_Œª ( italic_G ).

We give a detailed proof in Appendix A.3.6. The above theorem demonstrates the robustness of graph prompting methods across different types of GNN architectures, including those with non-linear attention mechanisms. The consistency of these results with our earlier findings for linear models suggests that the fundamental principles of graph prompting remain effective even as we move towards more complex and non-linear model architectures.

5 Experiments

5.1 Experimental Settings

Data Preparation: We first confirm our theoretical findings on synthetic datasets because these datasets offer controlled environments, allowing us to isolate specific variables and study their impacts. We generate these datasets by defining the dimension of graph feature vector (FùêπFitalic_F), average of graph node numbers (Na‚Å¢v‚Å¢gsubscriptùëÅùëéùë£ùëîN_{avg}italic_N start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_a italic_v italic_g end_POSTSUBSCRIPT), average of graph edge numbers (Ea‚Å¢v‚Å¢gsubscriptùê∏ùëéùë£ùëîE_{avg}italic_E start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_a italic_v italic_g end_POSTSUBSCRIPT), and number of graphs in the dataset (MùëÄMitalic_M). These parameters characterize both individual graphs and the entire dataset, facilitating our study of the relationship between these features and œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ. We further conduct the experiments on the real-world dataset in Appendix B, from which we can find similar observations.

Model Settings: We utilize two GNN frameworks: GCN (representing linear models) and GAT (representing non-linear models). We limit our experiments to these two models as other models follow similar patterns. Unless otherwise specified, we use a 3-layer GNN with Leaky-ReLU activation function and feature dimension F=25ùêπ25F=25italic_F = 25. For full-rank matrix studies, we ensure each layer‚Äôs matrix is full-rank (selected after pre-training). For non-full-rank matrix studies, we set the rank loss to 5 by default. The default ReadOut method is mean pooling.

Training: In the graph prompting training process, we perform gradient descent on the parameters œâùúî\omegaitalic_œâ of the graph prompt PœâsubscriptùëÉùúîP_{\omega}italic_P start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT using the Adam optimizer. We use a learning rate of 1√ó10‚àí41superscript1041\times 10^{-4}1 √ó 10 start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT - 4 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT and weight decay of 5√ó10‚àí55superscript1055\times 10^{-5}5 √ó 10 start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT - 5 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT. We implement an early stopping mechanism with a maximum of 2,000 epochs by default. Our loss function is defined as ‚ÄñFŒ∏‚àó‚Å¢(Gp)‚àíC‚Å¢(G)‚ÄñnormsubscriptùêπsuperscriptùúÉsubscriptùê∫ùëùùê∂ùê∫\|F_{\theta^{*}}(G_{p})-C(G)\|‚à• italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) - italic_C ( italic_G ) ‚à• for single-graph tasks, and ‚àëG‚ààùí¢‚ÄñFŒ∏‚àó‚Å¢(Gp)‚àíC‚Å¢(G)‚Äñ2/Msubscriptùê∫ùí¢superscriptnormsubscriptùêπsuperscriptùúÉsubscriptùê∫ùëùùê∂ùê∫2ùëÄ\sqrt{\sum_{G\in\mathcal{G}}\|F_{\theta^{*}}(G_{p})-C(G)\|^{2}/M}square-root start_ARG ‚àë start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G ‚àà caligraphic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ‚à• italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) - italic_C ( italic_G ) ‚à• start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT / italic_M end_ARG for multi-graph tasks where Gpsubscriptùê∫ùëùG_{p}italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT is the combined graph with Gùê∫Gitalic_G and graph prompt, and C‚Å¢(G)ùê∂ùê∫C(G)italic_C ( italic_G ) means an optimal function to the downstream task, which is not accessible without a specific task. Since the ultimate purpose of graph prompting is to approximate graph operation, we here treat C‚Å¢(‚ãÖ)ùê∂‚ãÖC(\cdot)italic_C ( ‚ãÖ ) as various graph data permutations such as adding/deleting nodes, adding/deleting/changing edges, and transforming features of a given graph Gùê∫Gitalic_G. Then we wish to see how well the graph prompt reaches C‚Å¢(G)ùê∂ùê∫C(G)italic_C ( italic_G ) by manipulating graph data with a graph prompt. For more detailed experimental settings, please check in the Appendix C.

5.2 On mapping to BGsubscriptùêµùê∫B_{G}italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT with single graph

According to Theorems 3, 4, and 9, error-free projection can be achieved in full-rank situations. Here we investigate convergence properties with a maximum of 5,000 epochs. Figure 3 presents the results for GPF and All-in-One prompts with GCN and GAT, respectively. From the results we can find that for single-graph, full-rank matrix scenarios, both GPF and All-in-one approaches show loss converging to zero, which is consistent with our theoretical findings.

5.3 On mapping to œµ‚Å¢-‚Å¢BGitalic-œµ-subscriptùêµùê∫\epsilon\text{-}B_{G}italic_œµ - italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT with single graph

Theorem 5 states that in non-full-rank situations, there exists an upper bound on the error. Here we extensively examine the relationship between various parameters and the error upper bounds in the context of non-full-rank matrices given a single graph. Since showing this upper bound in practice is usually intractable, we fix all other parameters and employ five pre-trained models. For each fixed pre-trained model, we conduct experiments and repeat each experiment 30 times. Then we take the maximum loss from these repetitions as the approximation to the upper bound.

Subsequently, we calculate the mean and standard deviation of these upper bounds to generate plots. The parameters of interest include rank loss (as shown in Figure 1 in section 4.1), node feature dimension (Figure 4a), graph size (Figure 4b), and model layer number (Figure 4c). Intuitively, with the increase of data complexity (e.g., larger features and graph size), the upper bound becomes larger in general. As the graph model becomes more complicated (e.g., layer number increase), the projected space becomes larger making the error bound intend to be smaller. When weight rank declines, the model‚Äôs capacity intends to poor results, making the error bound increase. More advanced graph prompts (e.g., All-in-One) usually have a lower error bound than the naive one (e.g., GPF). These observations can be naturally inferred from our theoretical analysis in section 4.1.

5.4 On mapping to œµ‚Å¢-‚Å¢BGitalic-œµ-subscriptùêµùê∫\epsilon\text{-}B_{G}italic_œµ - italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT with multiple graphs

Theorem 6 discusses a lower bound on the RMSE over the errors on multiple graphs with a single prompt token. In this section, we conducted experiments on the number of graphs in the dataset w.r.t the empirical minimum error. As shown in Figure 5a, the minimum error shows an upward trend and then tends to saturate, which is highly consistent with the findings in Theorem 6.

Theorem 7 suggests that for the graph prompt with multiple tokens and multiple graphs, a small kùëòkitalic_k tokens is sufficient to achieve good performance. In particular, we wish to see how the error (loss) changes as MùëÄMitalic_M (number of graphs) increases while kùëòkitalic_k remains fixed, and its counterpart case: how does the error change as kùëòkitalic_k increases while MùëÄMitalic_M remains fixed? Here we explored the relationship between the number of prompt tokens, the number of graphs in the dataset, and the error. We present experimental results in Figure 5b and Figure 5c, which indicate two surfaces. From these figures we can find that both GPF and All-in-One show similar effects: when the number of prompt tokens exceeds 10101010, the error becomes relatively small. As the number of prompt tokens increases further, the loss does not significantly decrease. Similarly, when the number of graphs increases and the number of prompt tokens is large, the decrease in error is also not that obvious.

6 Conclusion

This paper addresses the theoretical gap in graph prompting by introducing a comprehensive framework from a data operation perspective. We introduced the concepts of ‚Äúbridge sets‚Äù and ‚Äúœµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ-extended bridge sets‚Äù to formally demonstrate that graph prompts can approximate graph transformation operators, effectively bridging pre-trained models with downstream tasks without retraining. Our contributions are threefold: first, we established guarantee theorems confirming that graph prompts can simulate various graph data operations, explaining their effectiveness in aligning upstream and downstream tasks. Second, we derived upper bounds on the approximation errors introduced by graph prompts for both individual graphs and batches of graphs, highlighting how factors like model rank and prompt complexity influence these errors. Third, we analyzed the distribution of these errors and extended our theoretical findings from linear models like GCNs to non-linear models such as GATs, showcasing the robustness of graph prompting across different architectures. Our extensive experiments validate these theoretical results and confirm their practical implications, demonstrating that graph prompts can effectively leverage pre-trained models in various settings. By providing solid theoretical foundations, our work not only explains why graph prompts work but also guides the design of more effective prompting techniques. This empowers researchers and practitioners to utilize graph prompts with greater confidence, potentially leading to more efficient and generalized graph neural network models across diverse applications.

Appendix

The appendix of this paper is organized as follows: Appendix A presents the detailed theoretical content on the main findings in the paper. In order to reduce the bar of reading this content, we first give some preliminaries and definitions in Appendix A.1, followed by fundamental lemmas (Appendix A.2) that will be used to prove our theorems. In Appendix A.3, we carefully prove the theorems in the main body of this paper, followed by a further mathematical discussion in Appendix A.4. Beyond theoretical analysis, Appendix B presents additional experimental results on the real-world datasets, which have similar observations to the main experiments in the paper. Appendix C introduces more details on the settings of the experiment.

Appendix A Theoretical Analysis And Proofs

Reading Guideline: Appendix A ‚ÄúTheoretical Results and Proofs‚Äù is divided into four subsections:

  • ‚Ä¢

    A.1 Definitions and Preliminaries: Readers are advised to initially skip this subsection. It serves as a reference for unfamiliar terms encountered later in the text.

  • ‚Ä¢

    A.2 Fundamental Lemmas: These properties are essential components for proving the main theorems. We will clearly express what each lemma demonstrates. Readers are recommended to refer to this subsection when encountering these lemmas while reading the theorem proofs.

  • ‚Ä¢

    A.3 Detailed Proofs of Main Theorems: This subsection is recommended as the primary focus for readers. It contains the core ideas behind why prompts work, even though some lemmas may be required for complete understanding.

  • ‚Ä¢

    A.4 Additional Mathematical Lemmas: This subsection includes purely mathematical lemmas encountered during the proofs in A.2 or A.3. These lemmas are not directly related to GNN models or prompts. Readers are advised to review this subsection after reading the previous content.

A.1 Preliminaries And Definitions

A.1.1 Preliminaries

Preliminary 1 (GCN and GAT).

Graph Convolutional Networks (GCN) Kipf & Welling (2016) perform convolution operations on graph-structured data by aggregating feature information from a node‚Äôs neighbors. The recursive update rule for a GCN layer is:

Preliminary 2 (Pre-training and Fine-tuning vs Pre-training and Prompt).

Pre-training and Fine-tuning Zhu et¬†al. (2021)involves two stages: first, a model is pre-trained on a large dataset to learn general representations, and then it is fine-tuned on a specific downstream task.

Formally, let FŒ∏‚àósubscriptùêπsuperscriptùúÉF_{\theta^{*}}italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT be the pre-trained model and C‚Å¢(‚ãÖ)ùê∂‚ãÖC(\cdot)italic_C ( ‚ãÖ ) be the optimal mapping function that maps the original graph to the embedding vector of the downstream task (i.e., can be parsed to yield correct results for Go‚Å¢r‚Å¢isubscriptùê∫ùëúùëüùëñG_{o}riitalic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_o end_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_r italic_i in the downstream task)

Fine-tuning aims to adjust the model parameters from Œ∏‚àósuperscriptùúÉ\theta^{*}italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT to Œ∏#superscriptùúÉ#\theta^{\#}italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT # end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT so that:

FŒ∏‚àó‚ÜíŒ∏#‚Å¢(Gori)‚âàC‚Å¢(Gori).subscriptùêπ‚ÜísuperscriptùúÉsuperscriptùúÉ#subscriptùê∫oriùê∂subscriptùê∫oriF_{\theta^{*}\rightarrow\theta^{\#}}(G_{\text{ori}})\approx C(G_{\text{ori}}).italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Üí italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT # end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT ori end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) ‚âà italic_C ( italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT ori end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) . (11)

Pre-training and Prompting keeps the pre-trained model parameters fixed and instead modifies the input data to bridge the pre-training and downstream tasks. Specifically, it seeks a transformation from the original graph Gorisubscriptùê∫oriG_{\text{ori}}italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT ori end_POSTSUBSCRIPT to a prompt-enhanced graph Gbrisubscriptùê∫briG_{\text{bri}}italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT bri end_POSTSUBSCRIPT such that:

FŒ∏‚àó‚Å¢(Gbri)=C‚Å¢(Gori).subscriptùêπsuperscriptùúÉsubscriptùê∫briùê∂subscriptùê∫oriF_{\theta^{*}}(G_{\text{bri}})=C(G_{\text{ori}}).italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT bri end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) = italic_C ( italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT ori end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) . (12)

This approach leverages the frozen pre-trained model by adapting the input data through graph prompts, eliminating the need to fine-tune the model parameters.

Preliminary 3 (GPF and All-in-One).

Graph Prompt Frameworks introduce learnable modifications to input graphs to enhance the performance of frozen pre-trained GNNs on downstream tasks. Two primary frameworks are prompt token vectors like GPF/GPF-Plus Fang et¬†al. (2022) and prompt subgraph like All-in-One Sun et¬†al. (2023a).

GPF (Graph Prompt Feature) adds a prompt vector to each node‚Äôs feature vectors. All-in-One optimizes the prompt tokens and their connections to adapt the pre-trained model to downstream tasks without altering the model parameters.

Preliminary 4 (Diffusion Matrix).

Diffusion Matrix Gasteiger et¬†al. (2019) plays a crucial role in representing the diffusion process on a graph. Specifically, many GNN architectures can be expressed using the following formulation:

ùêá=ùêí‚ãÖùêó‚ãÖùêñ,ùêá‚ãÖùêíùêóùêñ\mathbf{H}=\mathbf{S}\cdot\mathbf{X}\cdot\mathbf{W},bold_H = bold_S ‚ãÖ bold_X ‚ãÖ bold_W , (17)

Where: ùêíùêí\mathbf{S}bold_S is the diffusion matrix, derived from the graph‚Äôs adjacency matrix and model structure, which governs how information propagates across the graph. ùêóùêó\mathbf{X}bold_X is the original node feature matrix. ùêñùêñ\mathbf{W}bold_W is the learnable weight matrix associated with the GNN layer. ùêáùêá\mathbf{H}bold_H is the node feature embedding matrix after message transformation and aggregation.

A.1.2 Definitions

We provide a glossary and default symbols meanings here for the reader‚Äôs convenience.

A.2 Fundamental Lemmas

This lemma serves as a foundational component for proving the theorem. However, readers may choose to skip the lemma initially and return to it when it is referenced in the theorem‚Äôs proof.

Default Case

By default, we consider the GNN model as a surjective mapping operator from the graph set {G}ùê∫\{G\}{ italic_G } to ‚ÑùFsuperscript‚Ñùùêπ\mathbb{R}^{F}blackboard_R start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_F end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, obtained after pre-training tasks. This operator can provide sufficient information to express the correct results of the graph in the pre-training task. (For instance, through a task-specific head mapping to the likelihood of a 0/1 decision.)

Notations

A.3 Proof of Theorem in the Paper

A.3.1 Bridge Graph Existence Theorem

Proof of Theorem 1

Proof.

For a given Go‚Å¢r‚Å¢isubscriptùê∫ùëúùëüùëñG_{ori}italic_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_o italic_r italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and a downstream task Td‚Å¢o‚Å¢wsubscriptùëáùëëùëúùë§T_{dow}italic_T start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_d italic_o italic_w end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, the embedding vector corresponding to the downstream task is formally defined as the embedding vector produced by the optimal downstream model for Td‚Å¢o‚Å¢wsubscriptùëáùëëùëúùë§T_{dow}italic_T start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_d italic_o italic_w end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, which is thus uniquely determined.

Given our previous definition for the default case A.2, the FŒ∏subscriptùêπùúÉF_{\theta}italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Œ∏ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT discussed here is a surjective mapping from the graph space {G}ùê∫\{G\}{ italic_G } to ‚ÑùFsuperscript‚Ñùùêπ\mathbb{R}^{F}blackboard_R start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_F end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT. Remark 4.

As Johnstone (2001) pointed out, the eigenvalues of V=C‚ä§‚Å¢Cùëâsuperscriptùê∂topùê∂V=C^{\top}Citalic_V = italic_C start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚ä§ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_C in datasets often exhibit a truncated eigenvalue distribution. The first k0subscriptùëò0k_{0}italic_k start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 0 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT eigenvalues explain most of the variance. Furthermore, Jolliffe & Cadima (2016) shows that in many datasets, eigenvalues may exhibit exponential decay. Hence, the sum of remaining eigenvalues decreases rapidly as kùëòkitalic_k increases. This could explain why moderate-scale prompts are sufficient to achieve good results on large graph datasets.

Remark 5.

Here, our equation¬†58 implicitly assumes that the first N‚àí1ùëÅ1N-1italic_N - 1 layers of GNN are of full rank. Therefore, we can still use this theorem for approximation.

Normal Distribution Assumption

We assume that the vector ùú∑ùú∑\bm{\beta}bold_italic_Œ≤, which we call the graph embedding residual vector, follows an FùêπFitalic_F-dimensional i.i.d. normal distribution with mean ùüé0\mathbf{0}bold_0 and variance cùëêcitalic_c:

ùú∑‚àºùí©‚Å¢(0,c‚Å¢IF)similar-toùú∑ùí©0ùëêsubscriptùêºùêπ\bm{\beta}\sim\mathcal{N}(0,cI_{F})bold_italic_Œ≤ ‚àº caligraphic_N ( 0 , italic_c italic_I start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_F end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) (61)

where IFsubscriptùêºùêπI_{F}italic_I start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_F end_POSTSUBSCRIPT is the F√óFùêπùêπF\times Fitalic_F √ó italic_F identity matrix.

Intuitively, this graph embedding residual vector ùú∑ùú∑\bm{\beta}bold_italic_Œ≤ represents the additional term that the graph needs to fit due to non-full-rank and non-linear components. Formally, its components are defined as:

[ùú∑]j=‚àëi=1N‚àí(Œ±)k‚Å¢wi‚Å¢vi‚Å¢j,where¬†‚Å¢k={0if¬†‚Å¢œÉ‚Å¢(ci‚Å¢pj‚Ä≤‚àíœÉ‚àí1‚Å¢(vi‚Å¢j))>0‚àí1otherwiseformulae-sequencesubscriptdelimited-[]ùú∑ùëósubscriptsuperscriptùëÅùëñ1superscriptùõºùëòsubscriptùë§ùëñsubscriptùë£ùëñùëówhere¬†ùëòcases0if¬†ùúésubscriptùëêùëñsubscriptsuperscriptùëù‚Ä≤ùëósuperscriptùúé1subscriptùë£ùëñùëó01otherwise[\bm{\beta}]_{j}=\sum^{N}_{i=1}-(\alpha)^{k}w_{i}v_{ij},\quad\text{where }k=% \begin{cases}0&\text{if }\sigma(c_{i}p^{\prime}_{j}-\sigma^{-1}(v_{ij}))>0\\ -1&\text{otherwise}\end{cases}[ bold_italic_Œ≤ ] start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_j end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = ‚àë start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_N end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i = 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT - ( italic_Œ± ) start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_k end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_w start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_v start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i italic_j end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , where italic_k = { start_ROW start_CELL 0 end_CELL start_CELL if italic_œÉ ( italic_c start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Ä≤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_j end_POSTSUBSCRIPT - italic_œÉ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT - 1 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ( italic_v start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i italic_j end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) ) > 0 end_CELL end_ROW start_ROW start_CELL - 1 end_CELL start_CELL otherwise end_CELL end_ROW (62)

The reasons behind this assumption are as follows: (1). Symmetry (2). The sum of random variables and Central Limit Theorem: Each Œ≤jsubscriptùõΩùëó\beta_{j}italic_Œ≤ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_j end_POSTSUBSCRIPT is a sum of multiple terms, each of which can be considered a random variable. The Central Limit Theorem suggests that its distribution should approach a normal distribution. (3). Continuous and smooth distribution (4). Independence: The components of ùú∑ùú∑\bm{\beta}bold_italic_Œ≤ are assumed to be independent due to the independence of the input features and the structure of the GNN.

Therefore, it is reasonable to assume that ùú∑ùú∑\bm{\beta}bold_italic_Œ≤ follows an FùêπFitalic_F-dimensional i.i.d. normal distribution with mean 0 and variance cùëêcitalic_c for some positive constant cùëêcitalic_c.

A.4 Further Mathematical Discussion

Discussion on ùê©ùê©\mathbf{p}bold_p:

In lemma 2, we rely on the claim that assumes Œî‚Å¢R=ùêúùê©0‚ä§ŒîùëÖsuperscriptsubscriptùêúùê©0top\Delta R=\mathbf{c}\mathbf{p}_{0}^{\top}roman_Œî italic_R = bold_cp start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 0 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚ä§ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT won‚Äôt lose the generality. Remark 6.

We demonstrate that the claim in Explanation A.4 does not affect the results in Theorems 6 and 7.

Theorem 6 is about the case of a single prompt, making the claim trivially true.

For Theorem 7, we are seeking an upper bound for the optimal case. Among all prompt parameters satisfying the claim, if we can obtain the result in 7. Then, based on the principle that the global minimum is less than or equal to any partial minimum, the error in the optimal prompt would only be smaller, making such upper bound smaller.

In conclusion, our assumption is valid.

Definition 3 (Minimum Projection Distance to Cone Surface).

Definition 4 (The angle to boundary and the aperture of the cone).

For any interior point xùë•xitalic_x of a convex cone Cùê∂Citalic_C, we define:

(i) The minimum distance from xùë•xitalic_x to the boundary of Cùê∂Citalic_C:

Appendix B Supplementary Experiments

We conducted supplementary experiments on real-world datasets to validate our results. We performed similar experiments as in the main text using entirely different datasets, namely NCI1 and DD Morris et¬†al. (2020). The NCI1 dataset has 37-dimensional node features, 4,110 subgraphs, an average of 29.87 nodes per subgraph, and an average of 64.60 edges per subgraph. The DD dataset has 89-dimensional node features, 1,178 subgraphs, an average of 284.32 nodes per subgraph, and an average of 1,431.32 edges per subgraph. Our results are shown in the following figures.

Exp1 we examined the loss curves during training for GPF and All-in-one prompting methods with full-rank matrices. Similar to observations from synthetic datasets, the prompt method shows a period of steady decline followed by a rapid decrease to a small magnitude, then slowly converging to zero. This aligns with our theoretical results.

Exp 2 we investigated the relationship between empirical maximum error and rank loss for non-full-rank matrices. The results here are similar to those in the main text, with loss (empirical maximum error) increasing as rank loss increases. Where rank loss is rùëüritalic_r means the rank of weight matrix WùëäWitalic_W in GNN is n‚àírùëõùëün-ritalic_n - italic_r.

Exp 3 We examined how the RMSE of GPF or single-node All-in-one Prompt methods change as the number of graphs increases in multiple graph mapping scenarios. We observed that in real-world datasets, RMSE also increases rapidly as the number of graphs increases, which aligns with our observation in the main experiment.

Appendix C EXPERIMENT DETAILS

Data Preparation: We first confirm our theoretical findings on synthetic datasets because these datasets offer controlled environments, allowing us to isolate specific variables and study their impacts. These parameters characterize both individual graphs and the entire dataset, facilitating our study of the relationship between these features and œµitalic-œµ\epsilonitalic_œµ. In detail, the distribution of graph node feature vectors is set to a normal distribution ùí©‚Å¢(0,1)ùí©01\mathcal{N}(0,1)caligraphic_N ( 0 , 1 ); the graph edge density œÅùúå\rhoitalic_œÅ is set to 0.150.150.150.15, where œÅùúå\rhoitalic_œÅ represents the probability of an edge existing between any two nodes.

Model Settings: We utilize two GNN frameworks: GCN (representing linear models) and GAT (representing non-linear models). We limit our experiments to these two models as other models follow similar patterns. Unless otherwise specified, we use a 3-layer GNN with Leaky-ReLU activation function and feature dimension F=25ùêπ25F=25italic_F = 25. For full-rank matrix studies, we ensure each layer‚Äôs matrix is full-rank (selected after pre-training). For non-full-rank matrix studies, we set the rank loss to 5555 by default. The default ReadOut method is mean pooling.

Training: In the graph prompting training process, we perform gradient descent on the parameters œâùúî\omegaitalic_œâ of the graph prompt PœâsubscriptùëÉùúîP_{\omega}italic_P start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_œâ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT using the Adam optimizer. We use a learning rate of 1√ó10‚àí41superscript1041\times 10^{-4}1 √ó 10 start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT - 4 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT and weight decay of 5√ó10‚àí55superscript1055\times 10^{-5}5 √ó 10 start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT - 5 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT. We implement an early stopping mechanism with a maximum of 2000 epochs by default. When analyzing the upper bound of the error of the prompt method, it is crucial to ensure that the convergence value of PùëÉPitalic_P is indeed the global minimum. To prevent the training of prompt parameters from falling into local minima, we approximate the global minimum by independently training kùëòkitalic_k times with random initialization for each prompt, and selecting the minimum loss. Typically, kùëòkitalic_k is set to 3.
